column7: Why Your Data Infrastructure Migration Project Will Fail (And How to Succeed)
column9:
View this post on the web at https://seattledataguy.substack.com/p/why-your-data-infrastructure-migration

Hi, fellow future and current Data Leaders; Ben here üëã
Today, we are going to dive into migration projects and what can hold them back from succeeding. 
But before we jump in, I wanted to share a bit about Estuary [ https://substack.com/redirect/bcaa0bb6-7a20-4e2a-9e17-7fa1bf893395?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], a platform I've used to help make clients' data workflows easier and am an adviser for. Estuary helps teams easily move data in real-time or on a schedule, from databases and SaaS apps to data lakes and warehouses, empowering data leaders to focus on strategy and impact rather than getting bogged down by infrastructure challenges. If you want to simplify your data workflows, check them out today.
Now let‚Äôs jump into the article!
Intro
If you work in tech long enough, you‚Äôll inevitably find yourself in the middle of a migration project‚Äîprobably more often than you‚Äôd like.
‚ÄúWe should all use Teradata!‚Äù Migrate.
‚ÄúActually, Snowflake is the future!‚Äù Migrate.
‚ÄúWait, let‚Äôs go all-in on Iceberg and Databricks!‚Äù Migrate.
It‚Äôs a never-ending cycle. In fact, migration is such a core part of the industry that Databricks recently acquired BladeBridge just to help them make migrations easier.
The problem? Migrations often don‚Äôt go as planned. Some get delayed, others stall out halfway, and many become massive time and money sinks. There are countless ways for a migration to go sideways, but with the right approach, you can avoid the most common pitfalls.
Let‚Äôs break down the biggest reasons migration projects fail‚Äîand how you can keep yours on track.
Lack of a Plan
I‚Äôve been involved in plenty of migrations [ https://substack.com/redirect/73cc3e6f-c122-480c-9515-91551234eb3e?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]‚Äîsome smooth, some absolute nightmares. The difference? A solid plan.
You can‚Äôt just say, ‚ÄúLet‚Äôs migrate to Databricks [ https://substack.com/redirect/5f00fa37-6e80-4ced-9943-828212257e75?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]!‚Äù or ‚ÄúSnowflake [ https://substack.com/redirect/754339b5-527e-4e2c-9c2d-13d8c695eab9?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] is the way to go!‚Äù and hope for the best (gotta be fair to both). Without a structured approach, things will get messy fast.
At a minimum, you need to:
List everything that needs to be migrated‚Äîtables, workflows and any other objects and artifacts.
Prioritize the order of migration‚Äîsome dependencies need to move first.
Secure buy-in from beyond engineering‚Äîmigrations impact more than just the data team [ https://substack.com/redirect/a211e404-dc9a-4561-b3fb-5fb8f4973ae8?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
You‚Äôd be surprised how many projects I‚Äôve walked into where there was no clear plan. I‚Äôd ask around for a checklist of what needed to be migrated, and no one had one. Instead, people were trying to track everything in their heads‚Äîa guaranteed way to forget something critical.
So, start by listing out every object. Most databases let you access the information schema [ https://substack.com/redirect/162d8d01-133f-4ad6-87f4-ae2866c6b3f7?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], so pull a list of all tables, stored procedures, tasks, and anything else relevant.
For dashboards [ https://substack.com/redirect/36010218-3091-472a-8e05-206924c1e500?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], Excel reports, or other user-facing tools, you may need to manually gather details‚Äîunless you‚Äôre lucky enough to have a lineage tool. Truthfully, this is what made migration projects at Facebook much easier; I could easily list all the dependencies. Of course, coordinating across dozens of teams was still a challenge.
If you don‚Äôt have an automated way to track dependencies, get ahead of the problem. Ask every team that relies on your data warehouse [ https://substack.com/redirect/e1e87fce-f99e-47a8-be3f-b0952e79c7f2?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] to submit a list of what they need migrated‚Äîset a deadline, and hold them to it.
A little upfront planning can save you months of headaches.
SeattleDataGuy‚Äôs Newsletter is a reader-supported publication. To receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber.
Lack of Ownership
Some projects seem to start with a big announcement‚Äî‚ÄúWe need to migrate to XYZ platform‚Äù‚Äîbut then‚Ä¶ nothing. No clear owner, no defined process, just chaos.
Regardless of the project‚Äôs size or how many teams are involved, someone needs to own the migration. Without a clear leader, things fall apart.
I‚Äôve been part of both heavily centralized and federated migrations(completely decentralized migrations tend to fall apart), and the right approach tends to depend on factors like company size, workload, and who originally built the workflows and tables.
In a federated approach, the data team (likely) leads the migration, setting standards and providing tools while other teams move their own assets.
In a centralized approach, one dedicated team handles the entire migration, reducing fragmentation but increasing workload.
I have also rarely seen a purely decentralized approach lead to success as it often leads to a few key mistakes:
No central team overseeing the overall migration.
No requirement for teams to create a list and track what needs to be migrated
No clear definition of ‚Äúdone done.‚Äù
No prioritization, so migration takes a back seat to daily work.
And that‚Äôs how a 6-month migration turns into a 2-year headache. Thus, having a federated approach works better for larger migrations.
Migrations are hard. They take time. And they can‚Äôt succeed without someone driving them forward.
Lack of Testing
Testing isn‚Äôt optional‚Äîit‚Äôs essential. It doesn‚Äôt matter if you‚Äôre moving from Python 2 to Python 3, Oracle to SQL Server, BigQuery to Snowflake(or the other way around), or whatever the new tool is that people want to move to‚Äîyou need to verify that your data is actually the same post-migration.
I learned this when migrating from Oracle to SQL Server. We had a query that looked identical in both systems. Yet, when we ran it, we very quickly realized that the output was different. We had assumed null values would be sorted at the bottom, but SQL Server placed them at the top.
Same SQL [ https://substack.com/redirect/91f033fd-4420-4c44-9d61-b5bdc82072a9?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] statement. Different results.
This happens all the time. Teams assume that because they‚Äôve copied the data, it must be a match‚Äîbut different databases, ELT [ https://substack.com/redirect/404a1f30-1ebc-47c2-84b7-0df6140b8e8e?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] tools, and storage formats can introduce subtle changes. Like in the picture above where someone might have accidentally changed the data type and in turn altered the data.
And no, testing doesn't mean running a select * from query and manually reviewing each line.
Instead, use automated validation tools or write a simple script to compare tables across systems. If you don‚Äôt verify your data, you‚Äôll be in for a nasty surprise when users start noticing discrepancies.
It can be tempting to think, ‚ÄúWe‚Äôre just moving tables, the data will be fine.‚Äù But trust me‚Äîit‚Äôs worth double-checking.
Lack of Buy-in
A migration can be technically perfect and still fail‚Äîif no one actually wants to use the new system.
When it comes to migrations, you‚Äôre managing two key workflows:
Project Management
Change Management [ https://substack.com/redirect/e6f2c6a7-a500-4be9-b38d-359366c4ca24?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Ignore the second one, and you‚Äôll find yourself in a bitter 6-12-month slog where teams resist the change, tensions rise, and people are thrown under the bus if things go wrong.
Migrations aren‚Äôt flashy. They don‚Äôt come with the hype of AI or the excitement of a new product launch. They‚Äôre tedious, often frustrating, and‚Äîif you don‚Äôt get buy-in from end-users and the decentralized teams who need to do the work‚Äîcan lead to a never-ending cycle of complaints:
‚ÄúWell, the old tool was better because it did‚Ä¶‚Äù
‚ÄúThis new system is just making my job harder.‚Äù
‚ÄúI‚Äôve had to get used to queries taking longer but it‚Äôs ok.‚Äù
Passive-aggressive comments and complaints can kill momentum fast. And, a great way to have a migration fail is to technically succeed but have no one buy-in.
To avoid this, involve end-users early‚Äîbefore the decision is set in stone. You don‚Äôt need universal agreement (because good luck getting even three teams to agree on anything), but you do need key stakeholders to feel like they‚Äôve had a say. The earlier you bring them in, the less pushback you‚Äôll face later.
Final Thoughts
Migration projects are unavoidable. Maybe your company needs new capabilities, or maybe a VP is convinced that a new tool will magically solve all your company's problems. Either way, a successful migration takes more than just an announcement.
Without a solid plan, clear ownership, thorough testing, and real buy-in, a migration can quickly spiral into frustration, delays, and‚Äîworst of all‚Äîan unfinished project that drags on for years.
The key? Put in the work upfront. Track progress, hold teams accountable, and don‚Äôt assume everything will just work itself out. A little planning now can save a lot of pain later.

Dear friends,

In last week‚Äôs letter (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWFtLN5kQYNLW6M4jr61XPGy-W91lZlN5DZJzkN1TFhw03prCCW95jsWP6lZ3kDW3h25zd1BgCMWW6pZG4Z2BXWXTW8qQjGN4JKwc0W85nQHx8dVmzxW4_wnWq7P4DT7Vl1ydn1DjT4yN7d99Mh4xK6PW33FVHl8XSysDW4WFQbb5vmw1CW5ySWH27_mzQNVsJpm-2gwXpzW7N8yCy7cXM-3VjjW_v8mfY2GN1T1gpSX9_JFW9d6t_-4QTVXZW2MJcCY5lJN-7W6GTbD11wSx52W1KNsjk1qnK-9N7KsWHksvXvZW4Y-_Cn4xJBFrV-SSBv2vFpd1W7S2GCr29tLbBW1Qk-Cq7MVSGBW8_lHc-68gD5pW6zclT56qvdkbW18KjRg7qPTrXVqY5RH3tjMqKW7H16t81tqm-QW64kqy55j5bB9N8w0YB678-TVf6SSwbj04 ) , I explained how effective agentic AI development needs a disciplined evals and error analysis process, and described an approach to performing evals. This week, I‚Äôd like to summarize the core ideas behind error analysis and describe some best practices. Given the rapid pace of improvement in LLMs, when error analysis points to a problem, your options for how to address it are greater than before. Let me explain.

Take the problem of building a basic Deep Research agent that searches the web to write a detailed report on a topic like ‚Äúrecent developments in black-hole science.‚Äù An agent might take a sequence of steps to generate the final report, such as (i) use an LLM to generate a handful of web search queries related to the topic, (ii) call a web-search API to get lists of results, (iii) use an LLM to identify the most promising sources to fetch, and (iv) ask the LLM to use these sources to write the report.

If the final report is subpar compared to the work of a human researcher following the same steps, the gap in performance could be from any of the steps. A basic error analysis procedure might involve gathering a sample set of topics where the output is subpar, and reading the results of every step of the workflow ‚Äî called the traces ‚Äî to see which step most frequently generated results materially worse than a human would have. This is very valuable for deciding what step to focus on improving.

A common misconception of error analysis is that it takes a lot of work to get started. The key principle is to look at the steps of the workflow and see which steps did a bad job on a given input, often by benchmarking to human level performance (HLP). Assuming we are automating a task where HLP is desirable, then the most important thing is to systematically examine traces to understand when the agent is falling short of HLP. And just as we can get started with evals using a quick-and-dirty initial cut at it (maybe using just a handful of examples) followed by iterating (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWFtLN5kQYNLW6M4jr61XPGy-W91lZlN5DZJzkN1TFhvK3prCCW8wLKSR6lZ3q5W8gBCxx3q_nDLW3b8lxp2jnzYRV4ymbx1GlWkXW65dy2w45qmNSW36fDhp189mmPW5XwNvH8XK-1tW7BsW8V82g5CNW6qxrjr5Pl7_PVkZtLK1rJ1lfW4MRr0T8Z-5LtW63hg0P501rwXW2RYFCb5dX9yyW78mXHV3dgpjWW4nTT9j8VWw6CW6Vw63V8RsxwLVrqjNR4N61DJVdXTsN2fpjPgW1Kc_2f5Hp3z3W6Mvr3t3LBgvHW1wd5w58501CkMfKFkr-pWtcW1NWD_k7TlxsZW5KqB-x708VsBW5L_vG681qSLNW61QQBJ84J2FvW3xKxzl2bC2XsW1m6BhH175QKYW5F7phm6b1lSZf625qpF04 ) to improve, so too with error analysis.

Specifically, it is fine to start by reading one or just a handful of traces informally to get a sense of what might be going wrong. For example, if you see that the web search query terms in your Deep Researcher ‚Äî step (i) above ‚Äî frequently make no sense, that points you to an initial area to focus your efforts on improving. As the system matures, you can move incrementally toward more rigorous error analysis. For example, you might eventually end up with a regularly refreshed dataset of thousands of examples where the performance is poor, and carry out rigorous evaluations that show exactly what percentage of the time each of the steps (i) - (iv) contributed to problems with the final output, and also in what specific ways those steps fell short.

This type of analysis is extremely useful for deciding where to focus your efforts to improve the overall agentic workflow‚Äôs performance!

In addition to improving the execution of individual steps, we can change how we decompose a complex task into steps. When it came to pipelines built using machine learning or deep learning rather than LLMs, I found that the structure of the workflow ‚Äî that is, how you decompose an overall task into a sequence of steps to be carried out ‚Äî changed rarely. It was a big deal to rearchitect this! But in the past couple of years, because LLMs are improving so rapidly, I see much more rapid iteration on the design of workflows.

For example, one very common pattern is ripping out scaffolding and letting the LLM do more. This is often a good move when you now have access to a smarter LLM than you did when you first built a workflow. For example, perhaps you once used an LLM to clean up downloaded web pages by removing navigational links, ads, extraneous HTML, and the like, before a separate LLM used the cleaned-up pages to write a report. Since LLMs have become smarter, you might decide to skip the first step and dump messier HTML into the final LLM without an initial clean-up step, which can introduce its own errors.

Another example: Perhaps a year ago, we used hard-coded rules to decide what web pages to fetch and when to fetch more, but today we might let an LLM-based agent make this decision more autonomously. As LLMs get smarter, I see many teams rearchitecting workflows to remove hard-coded steps or constraints that were previously needed to keep the system from going off the rails. One way to spot opportunities for doing this is if error analysis shows that a sequence of steps collectively underperforms compared to what a human might do, even though the performance of each individual step is good. This might indicate that the way those steps are carried out is too rigid.

I go through many more examples in the Agentic AI (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWFtLN5kQYNLW6M4jr61XPGy-W91lZlN5DZJzkN1TFhv63prCCW7lCdLW6lZ3nPW8RFVsl5d20qNW1rpFg33JHtb4W7ph3Tx9dgRx-W1YrX8280n7CCN7Kg7Kb2p7V7N84n5WcSwFnpW81M0rQ3x0gr9W8v-jS39b12HYW869MrN7wWz2fW2YQqdT6RJ7VJW4cNQ9l8wZ7CWN4jStl3hW7V-W46d7n04SsRljW4Lv2my1qkX2fW6FvSw52c_r20W44rPSf4WkXpVW1qXQKw2FTLVbW7sx0_R1Qv_BLN3WWj_QFHTX6M96QltJ2nxdW2Pkc2v6S_kHyW3NQb3V85nmDHN4lDw5HVyXb9W52rb-g4gJ81jf5K7k6W04 ) course. Check it out if you want to learn more about evals and error analysis.

Keep building!

Andrew

News

Reasoning Without ‚ÄúThinking‚Äù

Reasoning models typically learn to undertake a separate process of ‚Äúthinking‚Äù through their output of before they produce final response. Ant Group built a top non-reasoning model that can take similar steps as part of its immediate response.

What‚Äôs new: Ant Group, an affiliate of Alibaba and owner of the online payments provider Alipay, released Ling-1T, a huge, open, non-reasoning model that outperforms both open and closed counterparts.

- Input/output: Text in (up to 128,000 tokens), text out (up to 32,000 tokens)
- Architecture: Mixture-of-Experts (MoE) transformer, 1 trillion parameters, 50 billion parameters active per token
- Performance: Outperformed leading non-reasoning models in 22 of 31 benchmark tests of reasoning, math, coding, general knowledge, and writing.
- Availability: Weights free to download from HuggingFace (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWFtLN5kQYNLW6M4jr61XPGy-W91lZlN5DZJzkN1TFhv63prCCW7lCdLW6lZ3lCN65tx5ZYbNFdW2-R6Gc7DrSx0W4Nbdpn754c5-V_ylz53VlGVkW5pFwl57nHx-TW7R495n6-sFPxVqTtKz5lqP03W6lBhS76VSsv7W4C2S-r6K5_jVW1wd9W28pBJ91W4zq_dq845rBcW7FXwsc8-lwsgW7szfSx8n_FCCV1q2dh1Y927JW30xf875YZHv7W7BVGfc2PQxDxN2L55lrf2W4CW6SPvDQ6MDm7CW5vDddG58cjCsW7hhCxy21541hW626txY2tppv4VNl19n8yCxGFW8Y4d2P5SG7vzW1fJq322JxQCff1D2VPM04 ) and ModelScope (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWFtLN5kQYNLW6M4jr61XPGy-W91lZlN5DZJzkN1TFhv63prCCW7lCdLW6lZ3pcW1CHNMY4RKcV_W43xLbv16pzH9N5Ch1zm8SFq2W7CGlPw3BbfcmW5GDm385YFy-VN4wjGbVPJ4nNW2kGTwY6QlxfHN6D7n0gNR4t1Mxmc1z7_m-rVsW2MV6D-6ZHW4G3GJS87kl8dW8ks5R03VLkyJW8t6kJZ1FS81yW49qMHH4vxKXMVM7Gx28WfDWkW82q9mx5sLM9XW5G9tBb3mmtm4W6mNVQL1L5HZyW8KKhMg2gNPH7W2_3W0n8Fmw8yW18mcRl3hLwxtW3p83sx1JWg2QW58MD2G2bqVR4W5yMd9_4my2Pmf2NZKs004 ) for commercial and noncommercial uses under the MIT license, API $0.56/$0.112/$2.24 per million input/cached/output tokens via zenmux.ai (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWFtLN5kQYNLW6M4jr61XPGy-W91lZlN5DZJzkN1TFhtR3prCCW6N1vHY6lZ3n_W2FNb3K8wcxH9N8Dspxj435qmW8C8z6b3npTc8W70WrCr5ftB3-W7dY9Ns3XyTdnW2KMDwD2sgfCLW4jSMym7wNW6JN7996czgNCBmW22VL2X2Xs8plN3Vsp1vxmBgDW8mlPdM4l0BYsW87vvF_4H_nlVN3WtzT8SHTxdW5Tzjsv6L8cynF4mstvd5k8yVbBzwC2-8hyLW4qSHBQ5SJKh4W90VWBr8nW73RN794CV3KKPvcW7tQMR96g1GmTW5bHkwG4wBQ4TW1TQd1r8LF9W3f5w_YfY04 )
- Undisclosed: Training data, specific training methods

How it works: The team emphasized chain-of-thought reasoning in both the pretraining and fine-tuning phases of development, but it didn't train the model to undertake a separate reasoning, or thinking, process before producing its final output. This means the model can reason selectively depending on the input.

- The team pretrained Ling-1T on 20 trillion tokens. In the last part of pretraining, they used a curated subset in which over 40 percent consisted of chain-of-thought data.
- They fine-tuned the model via supervised fine-tuning on examples that were augmented with chains of thought via CoT-Evo (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWFtLN5kQYNLW6M4jr61XPGy-W91lZlN5DZJzkN1TFhtR3prCCW6N1vHY6lZ3lmW75m6kF4tD9YTW8jvVNl8CgvSjW4n0Ltf3Gbv3lW50TH0K60xZlcW3m4Q_C22GD2cW29jZRq3RFg6gW90Y1Kb6Rdfd7N7Q2y17y5MYwW7S3pk73fzJK1W82V0qp7l7cw_W4NKPr99hx2KCW3ml5_531S-gCW1mD3j76FBn7CW6B38Gl95tBlSW1xkmHs7wFvj_W574v-D3RTfQmW9837t27nrTPlW2znqbY9cH3j6W30MyL457g0NjW4WXHRw4xqHt6W10Zbrr8RP-m4W3JycsR4qnWBjf7ZvWDb04 ) . CoT-Evo takes a training dataset and generates and evolves chains of thought (CoTs) for each example in the dataset. It evolves CoTs by repeatedly scoring them, selecting them (based on score, difference from other CoTs, and random chance), and modifying them via an LLM. The team fine-tuned Ling-1T on the examples with the highest-scoring CoTs.
- In addition, they fine-tuned the model using a reinforcement learning algorithm developed internally called Linguistic-Unit Policy Optimization (LPO). Unlike GRPO and GSPO, LPO ‚Äútreats sentences as the natural semantic action units, enabling precise alignment between rewards and reasoning behavior,‚Äù the company said.

Results: In Ant Group‚Äôs tests, Ling-1T generally outperformed three top non-reasoning models: DeepSeek-V3.1-Teriminus (thinking mode disabled), Moonshot Kimi-K2-Instruct, and OpenAI GPT-5 (thinking mode disabled), as well as Google Gemini 2.5 Pro set to minimum thinking (128 tokens).

- Ling-1T achieved the highest performance on 22 of 31 benchmarks tested and best or second-best performance on 29 of 31 benchmarks that cover general knowledge, coding, math, reasoning, writing, and agentic tasks.
- It performed best in the math and reasoning categories, achieving the best performance in all benchmarks tested. For instance, on math questions in AIME 2025, Ling-1T achieved 70.42 percent accuracy, whereas the second-best model, Gemini 2.5 Pro set to minimum thinking, achieved 70.10 percent accuracy.

Yes, but: The team published results of only one agentic benchmark and admits to limited performance in this area. It says it will improve agentic performance in future releases.

Why it matters:  Ling-1T generally outperforms the mighty Kimi K2 and closes the gap between open and closed nonreasoning models. MCP Poses Security Risks

The ability to easily connect large language models to tools and data sources has made Model Context Protocol popular among developers, but it also opens security holes, research shows.

What‚Äôs new: Golan Yosef at Pynt, an API security firm, analyzed (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWFtLN5kQYNLW6M4jr61XPGy-W91lZlN5DZJzkN1TFhvq3prCCW7Y8-PT6lZ3q4W7D-blz3n7F3_W3VByTv9b01scW2JYjnL6J-PHHW1-rskK1pL_S9W2f_l6W4V214rW3-xBh48F--L7W8WVH7r7GFX8DW18h5Ww6Yyp1KW93gtk08k0CG2W5FfKNY2KYSg4W91T0dj54YqkvVpGJw55WXrPHW4V73wb60my0dW1CyfvZ2vqSN9W1KNmx_3SksgGW9f6xVj1tBKZKW2PcLsz2-NFr4W2sZ10W8smk3LW3_xJZ-62WpfrW6QjWxk4yRXyvW6JcmrV6lPYN9W425XFv50WvQHW3dxJ6p3xVqSRW6pHrT-7V38dKW4TgJyh6_CMbkW8vKZfD7mzkmyf2bNzxM04 ) security risks of Model Context Protocol (MCP) servers. The work shows that when systems use multiple MCP servers, vulnerabilities rise rapidly.

How it works: MCP‚Äôs flexible, modular, dynamic design is a double-edged sword. It supports open-ended agentic interactions, but those very qualities make MCP servers vulnerable to exploitation. The study assessed security risks across more than 280 popular servers.

- For each server, Yosef evaluated two properties: whether it would process inputs from unsafe sources that can‚Äôt be fully verified or controlled (such as emails, chats, Slack messages, or scraped web pages) and whether it allowed powerful actions like code execution, file access, or calling APIs. He deemed servers that had both traits to be high-risk, since it could execute an attacker‚Äôs instructions without a user‚Äôs approval.
- He estimated how risk increases as systems use greater numbers of servers. (He didn‚Äôt disclose the formula or method used to derive the estimates.)
- He validated his risk model by attacking real-world MCP setups, including cases where unsafe input from one server caused another server to execute commands automatically.

Results: The study identified widespread patterns of vulnerability that compound as systems add MCP servers.

- Of the servers tested, 72 percent of servers tested exposed at least one sensitive capability to attackers, and 9 percent of servers tested were deemed high-risk.
- 13 percent of servers accepted inputs from unsafe sources, enabling attackers without direct access to their targets to deliver malicious text (HTML, emails, Markdown) that servers downstream might interpret as code.
- Risk of an exploitable configuration compounded rapidly with the first few servers added before flattening. Combining 2 servers created 36 percent chance of a vulnerable configuration, Combining 3 reached 52 percent chance, 5 servers exceeded 71 percent change, and 10 servers approached 92 percent chance.
- The study documents real-world examples in which attackers executed privileged actions. In one case, a plug-in web scraper fetched HTML, supplied by an attacker, that a Markdown parser interpreted as commands, which a shell plug-in duly executed.

The change prevents unauthorized access to MCP servers, but it doesn‚Äôt prevent malicious or malformed data from flowing between servers and triggering unintended actions.

Why it matters: Securing individual MCP servers is important but not sufficient, because vulnerabilities can emerge from interactions among servers. Adding more servers can make a system more agentic, but it also compounds vulnerabilities. The study suggests that developers mitigate this ‚Äúcompositional risk‚Äù by using only the servers they need, constraining what each one is allowed to do, and testing transfers of data among them.

In addition, SB 243 (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWFtLN5kQYNLW6M4jr61XPGy-W91lZlN5DZJzkN1TFhv63prCCW7lCdLW6lZ3pnW8jbFgF8hx9ZDW88JHwm77ZpxcW7qbY5m5qHnSFW6DSXgx4zXhbPW1JyY7c7NYplHW2m0B928325qwN2CKsvK20ffKW8KPPbs7R8GwmW7hM78B6C5JKHVj9mLz5XfC90W7jZS-S6Y7L6CW7JZXnq3-sv6gW3zGHjM8swvdjW5n7gl68M2pF1VwHFr340pJzBW57rwjz7ypPvNW4qtLPn5NXbZ3W2LlqVH4mcTq7W5NrhYR5NPt7rN8PJ_MwKmYrFW6V-lRR1kYjtlW2z8Rwd7PgbCTW6mkkjs1Mzyy6W7QR4J07_T7k2ds_QBY04 ) regulates chatbots, AB 316 (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWFtLN5kQYNLW6M4jr61XPGy-W91lZlN5DZJzkN1TFhv63prCCW7lCdLW6lZ3l4W8r_ppq7jPMkqW12Sb8w2cjrnCW5DcHtV7SMVV9N1vJcrSKvwtRW5g99GT87j8ZSW82kPSX5ldWpPW64cFWX6R8L-FW98qBM65hJCYzW2kXmnP3-Dv4PW9kV7hw5tHxV2W4RKCK24-gTKNN1cfBxGxj1gwW6xYT6L7KGhp4W1FjYLx51RYPXW11gpgz2t9YykW5ssclX8C76-vW5qK8Mk7SzNfRN5Jbf_pjcqLdW4tbW295ykjDLW2-GvkP6jpNCZW5nhdgP1BZnDgW6CWBmm1fcnwfW62Ssln87jt2xW1nWfgp8t0x4cf7zcSP804 )  makes developers liable for the actions of autonomous systems they build, and AB 853 (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWFtLN5kQYNLW6M4jr61XPGy-W91lZlN5DZJzkN1TFhv63prCCW7lCdLW6lZ3mKW8Nq9W774SpLYW44fsJw8xVnVDN1BZXBjCJ72ZW3cKkwT2X40Z7W7JcQ-54yKzY3W2xttyP1m_XZSW1Jq3LK1dwccYW8cYgMr5BlT-hW5Xqvgx13gKLjM5L_zThDntfW3hDy6B36Vh1KVsGV311wS8SSW1V4gLM1j6KqmW9lwDC36VbMbvW6GwhhR3NJw0rW42Smyv5XncvHW56txCr7VD8ysW1bdHsJ19lD24Vqv9BV1vP-FTN2gCwcMZ5vq-W95x1z24m1lz-W2SKhfT7H15-KW5XS0Gp2ylcqdW7XV9mk2C8g4Lf4H8zTn04 ) requires AI-generated media to be labeled clearly.

How it works: Together, the bills don‚Äôt ban any particular applications outright or restrict AI development, but they require extensive disclosures, either to the state or directly to users. Some took effect immediately while others, such as SB 243, will phase in by January 2027.

- SB 53 requires that developers of frontier models, defined as those whose training requires processing greater than 1026 integer or floating-point operations ‚Äî a level currently associated with very large and powerful models ‚Äî provide more transparency about their models‚Äô capabilities and potential risks. It also requires that developers with annual revenue above $500 million publish safety frameworks that show how they follow industry and international standards and assess and mitigate risk. In addition, they must report on their models‚Äô uses and capabilities at release and report any critical safety incidents within 15 days. Noncompliant developers could face fines of up to $1 million. The law protects whistleblowers within AI companies against retaliation and provides anonymous channels to report illegal or unsafe behavior. The bill takes effect in June 2026.
- SB 243 aims to prevent chatbots from harming minors and other vulnerable users. It bars exposing minors to sexual content and requires developers to disclose that chatbots are AI-generated and provide a general warning that chatbots may not be suited for minors. The bill also requires developers to provide specific support to users who discuss suicide or self-harm and to issue an annual report on mental health issues related to using their chatbots.
- AB 316 prohibits defendants in lawsuits from shifting responsibility onto AI systems by claiming that they harmed plaintiffs autonomously. It applies to anyone who develops, modifies, or uses an AI system.
- AB 853 requires that AI-generated media be labeled clearly as such. Furthermore, it requires that all media (AI-generated or not) include information about who made it and how. The bill requires that cameras, audio recorders, computers, and other media-capture devices record such provenance data, and that large-scale media distributors (2,000,000 monthly active users or more) disclose it.

column1: Honing an agent‚Äôs prompt can yield better results than fine-tuning the underlying large language model via reinforcement learning.
What‚Äôs new: Lakshya A. Agrawal and colleagues at UC Berkeley
column7: an algorithm that improves the performance of agentic systems by improving their prompts. The authors position it as an efficient alternative to fine-tuning an agent‚Äôs large language model via reinforcement learning.

column1: Key insight: Agentic models trained via reinforcement learning typically must take a complicated series of actions to earn a simple reward
column2: including calling a large language model multiple times for different purposes
column4: of the workflow. But a well designed prompt can take into account the various problems an agent may run into and thus guide the model more efficiently. The trick is to write prompts that anticipate such problems. To accomplish this
column5: a large language model can analyze an agent‚Äôs behavior as it responds to a given prompt

column8: and compose a more effective prompt.

column1: How it works: Prompting agents based on Alibaba‚Äôs Qwen3-8B
column2: the authors used GEPA to hone their performance on specific benchmarks. The method iteratively evolves a pool of candidate prompts
column3: beginning with a simple prompt for each LLM call a module of the agent makes
column4: such as ‚ÄúRespond to the query‚Äù or ‚ÄúEnsure the response is correct and adheres to the given constraints [specified in the benchmark inputs].‚Äù In each cycle
column7: and evaluates a prompt to generate a revised prompt that produces better results.

column1: - Given each prompt to be fed to the LLM (initially the default prompts
column2: later revised prompts selected for their effectiveness)
column3: the agent responds to a random subset of examples from a benchmark‚Äôs training set.

column2: alternating between the various modules. A separate Qwen3-8B instance examines the agent‚Äôs traces (generated text
column4: and results) and revises the prompt.

column1: - GEPA evaluates the revised prompt in a two-step process. First it feeds it to the agent along with the examples used previously and the prompts by other modules. If the revised prompt improves the agent‚Äôs performance
column2: GEPA adds it to a pool of candidate prompts and then scores its performance on each example in the benchmark‚Äôs validation set.
GEPA identifies prompts that achieved the highest score on at least one example. It selects a set of prompts (one for each module) for the next round of revision
column3: prioritizing prompts that excelled on multiple questions.

column7: The Inconvenient Truths of Self-Service Analytics
column9:
View this post on the web at https://seattledataguy.substack.com/p/the-inconvenient-truths-of-self-service

Hi, fellow future and current Data Leaders; Ben here üëã
I‚Äôve been speaking with data leaders and executives for the past few years about how to make data useful. And of course, self-service analytics comes up frequently. Some people believe in it, others don‚Äôt. So let‚Äôs talk about it!
But before that, if you're a data leader looking to understand what is going on in the broader data world as well as elevate your leadership skills, consider signing up for my 6-Week Data Leaders Playbook Accelerator program [ https://substack.com/redirect/f7ef9a87-4901-4ef9-968f-1d26f7d55505?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] that I will be running in September!
Now let‚Äôs jump into the article!
Self-service analytics is a hoax. A myth. The so-called holy grail.
If you‚Äôve worked in data long enough, you‚Äôve heard that line.
Maybe you‚Äôve even thought it yourself, like the time your CEO asked for a ‚Äúquick data pull‚Äù despite you building them a perfectly good dashboard that already answered the question.
When I first entered the data world, self-service analytics was everywhere. Tableau was pushing it hard, then Salesforce bought them for $15.7 billion, and every vendor promised it would free analysts from endless requests.
A decade later, we‚Äôre still chasing that dragon.
Now the narrative has shifted: dashboards are ‚Äúdead,‚Äù or the problem was that Tableau and Looker just ‚Äúnever did it right.‚Äù
Say that self-service is a failure in the wrong room, and someone will tell you, ‚ÄúYou were just doing it wrong.‚Äù
Wherever you stand on the debate, I want to explore where self-service has struggled, and what might actually work next.
Self-Service‚Äôs Inconvenient Truths
Here are a few uncomfortable truths that even the strongest believers in self-service can‚Äôt deny:
It‚Äôs been over a decade‚Ä¶ and companies of all sizes are still struggling to answer basic questions. Instead of fixing the root cause, they just keep migrating tools, hoping the next one will magically solve everything.
Dashboard fatigue is real [ https://substack.com/redirect/812d188f-c23f-4b47-bc40-e857a61a4555?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. Many companies have thousands of dashboards collecting dust, while no one remembers who built them or why.
Executives don‚Äôt want ‚Äúdashboard homework.‚Äù Executives don‚Äôt want a dashboard with 30 filters that they have to spend an hour configuring correctly. 
Sometimes the pursuit of self service in itself is the problem. Instead of making decisions a company will keep pushing to get to some undefined point on a map where they believe self service exists.
The numbers are still hard to find. Leaders continue to complain they can‚Äôt locate the ‚Äúright‚Äù metrics, because the same KPI exists in three dashboards with three slightly different definitions.
If a golden process existed, we‚Äôd already be using it. There‚Äôs no silver-bullet setup for self-service analytics; if there were, it would be industry standard by now.
Excel is still king. Like it or not, the only truly universal self-service analytics tool is a spreadsheet.
And sure, maybe your company has something that actually resembles ‚Äútrue‚Äù self-service. In my experience, the companies that have self service have modified the term to fit their needs.
But wait, GPT5 was just released, AI is the answer right?
SeattleDataGuy‚Äôs Newsletter is a reader-supported publication. To receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber.
AI Can Fix It Right?
‚ÄúAI will fix it all‚Ä¶ right?‚Äù
That‚Äôs the promise. All the headaches of self-service analytics, gone overnight.
Just add AI.
So far, I haven‚Äôt seen anything that removes the need for engineers or analysts [ https://substack.com/redirect/f7f33e78-fac1-41f8-be6c-b8e893dcf5e5?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. Data still has to be cleaned, pre-processed, and structured. Example queries still have to be created and provided to give a baseline. And even then, end users inevitably run into walls.
You still need guardrails, otherwise you‚Äôre handing someone a loaded gun they‚Äôll promptly aim at their own foot [ https://substack.com/redirect/ae9aae4a-9aa8-42ba-917a-657f6e0b762b?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
And that‚Äôs just the technical side.
On the people side, I had a CEO who is focused on solving the problem of text to insights share that people are bad at prompting. They are lucky if their end-user types in a dozen words requesting data.
‚ÄúCan you pull this data real quick on sales‚Äù - Ok, that‚Äôs a bit of a joke I am sure it‚Äôs better than that.
But if you‚Äôve ever built a dashboard for an executive, this will sound familiar. They don‚Äôt want to click through 30 filters. They don‚Äôt want to sift through 20 charts. They want answers, clear, concise, and ready to use. They‚Äôve got 15 major decisions to make today, and hunting for a single data point isn‚Äôt one of them.
Maybe AI doesn‚Äôt have to serve the CEO yet. Maybe the real win is getting the right information to VPs, directors, and operations managers, the people making day-to-day decisions.
But let‚Äôs put AI aside for a moment and talk about what you can actually do today to make your ‚Äúself-service‚Äù analytics, if we can even call it that, better.
A Practical Guide to Building Data Tools That Drive Action
Alright, so what do you do if you do want something close to self service?
Actually perhaps I should rephrase, how do you get to a point where you build useful data tools. Where business users want to take action.
Here are a few tips as well as bits of advice from data leaders other than myself.
Don‚Äôt Let Vendors Define Self-Service For You
A mistake many data leaders make in general is not defining the problem space they are actually trying to solve for. Instead, they jump straight to Google or ChatGPT and look up the best ETL or dashboarding tools, click the top choice from a vendor written article and get sucked into a vendor's pipeline. If the account executive is any good on the other side, they‚Äôll make sure to pitch their tool as the solution, even if it‚Äôs a bad fit(I‚Äôve seen it time and time again). They‚Äôll make sure their tool fits their definition of self service since you don‚Äôt have your own
It‚Äôs crucial you define self-service yourself both for external conversations with vendors as well as with internal users.
Develop A Bias For Action 
One problem with a lot of self-service initiatives is that business users will gather information from dashboards or reports, but not do anything with it. If the data isn‚Äôt driving any form of action or follow-up questions, what was the point? So develop dashboards with a clear end set of actions. Maybe that‚Äôs just for the end user to have better framing for future questions or perhaps you want to feed the results into an automated system. But be clear what you want to happen and what your goals are on the other side. Or you could just build yet another dashboard.
Accept That There Is A Spectrum
Self-service is not a destination. It‚Äôs a spectrum. At one company you might have business users who are highly proficient when it comes to working with data. At others the dashboards might be more of a jumping off point that helps guide conversations or bring up better questions.
Still other companies still require you to put in tickets for data requests to the data team who then has to go to IT who gives them access to the data only to figure out it was the wrong question the entire time.
Understand Why And Who You‚Äôre Building For
I recently wrote an article discussing this topic, but you want to make sure whatever you‚Äôre building, whether it‚Äôs a data set or a dashboard, it has a clear use case. That all starts with you asking good questions to your business counter parts. 
Perhaps that breaks the dream for self service analytics for some business users. After al, shouldn‚Äôt you just be able to go to a tool and get all the answers you need?
Well, I‚Äôd say we are far from that, despite what some vendors might say, so you‚Äôll likely need the article belwo.
Support a Culture of Asking Good Questions 
Teach users to ask better questions. Once your stakeholders have the data in front of them, what would they do. Would then need even more information to make a decision?
Sometimes the end-user may have not even asked themselves these questions. They know they‚Äôd like to know some numbers but they aren‚Äôt sure why or what they‚Äôd do once they did finally get the answer.
Even if they had AI giving them all the right answers, they need to still have the right follow-ups and understanding of the business to, well act.
But don‚Äôt just take my word for it, here are a few other perspectives from data leaders.
Simplify and Improve your dashboards - Honestly most dashboards aren‚Äôt great for people who don‚Äôt stare at data all day. They include way too many unnecessary metrics and filters, use terms that the end user wouldn‚Äôt recognize, and don‚Äôt guide the end user to actual insights. Shadow someone while they‚Äôre using the dashboard and give them a few questions to try to answer with the data and you‚Äôll learn a lot very quickly about how to improve it
-Laurie Stark [ https://substack.com/redirect/f9496ad9-832c-4de1-a46a-57a3c81f515d?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Another bit of advice from Charles Wickman [ https://substack.com/redirect/39551ba4-a822-414a-9b04-af6b00e1c5a5?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] was broader.
The analytics industry needs to rebrand and rethink what self service analytics means. In fact, let's ditch the term all together since it frankly has left a bad taste in many people‚Äôs mouths.
Final Thoughts
There has been a lot of talk about what the best way to get to self service analytics. Recently with AI many people have discussed semantic layers(of course semantic layers are far from new). But every time I talk to people who pose that idea I find that they‚Äôve never actually had it built in production. Or they had to spend a lot of time to do so.
It‚Äôs not to say I haven‚Äôt seen companies that have some flavor of self-service analytics. But if a company is just hoping that their Tableau subscription or Sigma contract will get them to the finish line, they‚Äôve got a long journey ahead.
There is still a good amount of work in between your raw data and all the answers your company desires. 
But you better believe all BI vendors(not just the ones I listed above) will happily take your money whether you get the results you want or not.
As always, thanks for reading.

Articles Worth Reading
There are thousands of new articles posted daily all over the web! I have spent a lot of time sifting through some of these articles as well as TechCrunch and companies tech blog and wanted to share some of my favorites!
Building a world-class data org
By Lenny Rachitsky  
Jessica Lachs is the global head of analytics and data science at DoorDash, where she‚Äôs built one of the largest and most respected data organizations in tech. In her more than 10 years at DoorDash, she has served as the first general manager, responsible for launching new markets; the head of business ops and analytics; and the VP of analytics and data science. Previously, Jessica founded GiftSimple, a social gifting startup, and started her career at Lehman Brothers as an investment banking analyst.
She shares so many valuable insights in this chat with Lenny you don‚Äôt want to miss it!
Listen/Read Here [ https://substack.com/redirect/bc750bd9-8b27-4aef-9c28-5dd5dbccd80d?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
How to Escape the Ad-Hoc Data Request Trap - 4 Mindset Shifts From a Former Director Of Analytics
Over the past few weeks, I‚Äôve been running a series of webinars with experienced data leaders, folks with decades of hands-on experience.
One of those sessions was titled ‚ÄúFrom Reactive to Proactive: Managing Stakeholders to Unlock Strategic Data Work.‚Äù
It turned into a standout conversation with Celina Wong [ https://substack.com/redirect/17e9c976-df0a-42d5-9781-6ff975a3682c?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], who‚Äôs led data teams at companies like Ulta and Poppins and recently served as CEO of a data consulting firm. We dug into a problem that nearly every data team wrestles with.
Too often, data teams get stuck in reactive cycles, pulling data, building dashboards, and answering questions as they come. Over time, that leads to hundreds (or thousands) of assets that no one actually uses. Worse, a lot of them were never aligned to the business strategy in the first place.
So how do you break the cycle?
How do you shift your data team from reactive responders to strategic partners?
